The architects saw - there is also a kindergarten in the office
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
But who would expect a mini kindergarten here, with everything that belongs to it: colorful walls, creative furniture, a lot of toys and even a mini playground on the outdoor terrace.
This kindergarten has been available to the staff of Arch.Design since last year.
The design and architecture office Arch.Design, whose studios come from a number of well-known Brno buildings, calculated from the first designs for the new building Avriopoint with the premises for its company mini-kindergarten.
Wisely, because most of his 90 employees are in the Babyboom Age and the company is committed to the projectors returning to their workplaces as soon as possible.
Together with the opportunity to work shorter, the Kindergarten is another bonus that Arch.Design has to offer its employees in the concept of its social programme.
The construction engineers have the ease to put their demanding job and child care under a hat.
The Mini Kindergarten is an original idea of the staff of Arch.Design and with the support of the management they managed to win funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The Operational Programme for Human Resources and Employment Policy is financed by the European Social Fund and by the State budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to this financing (subsidies of CZK 2, 8 million) the necessary facilities and equipment could be obtained and for the duration of 2 years qualified staff and operations were provided.
After the exploitation of the funding (2 years), the company Arch.Design is obliged to continue to operate the Minikindergarten for 3 additional years at its own expense.
The preparation of this project took place for a whole year, with the company Economy Rating providing active assistance in the processing of applications.
The children take care of fully qualified staff - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, the kindergarten can visit children without age restrictions, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is a mini kindergarten, only 5 children can be present at the same time, but the day over several children will change.
The kindergarten is flexible to the needs of the parents, the children of all employees have the same rights with regard to the use of the kindergarten - without regard to the corporate hierarchy and their respective position.
Although it is individual education and care, the programme content in the Mini Kindergarten is nevertheless comparable to the framework programme of pre-school education.
The children not only play here, especially they are given excellent lessons - from basic insights to preschool lessons, they also learn English.
The classroom is not only equipped with toys and creative games, but also with a computer that is available to the children.
What is more - the presence of young children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive company environment.
Parents can at any time take a look at the children and thus the stress is avoided when the children are picked up from a far away kindergarten.
Parents therefore use their working time more productively.
No wonder there are also natural and loyal employers-employees-relations here.
Arch.Design thus joined the Czech companies, which offer significant benefits when recruiting new employees, who are family-friendly and through such programs strengthen their personal marketing.
A bone house still fascinates after 100 years. Look at Gaudi’s interiors
The roof faces like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are torn fish mules.
This is the Casa Batlló of the Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
From the local inhabitants the house was nicknamed "Knochenhaus" with its organic forms.
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile splits and mosaics, the facades reminiscent of sheds and ubiquitous soft lines, all these are typical features of Antonio Gaudi's Art Nouveau style.
The facade of the house plays with dreamy lines, tender colors and textures that remind of nature and beings.
Only when you look at it more closely can you see that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and thoughtful order.
During the night, the whole facade still seems plastic, more dramatic and the special lighting enhances the shine of the colors.
The same swinging lines and devoured shapes also dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-shaped wood copies the window frames, rails, decorative elements of doors, even guck holes and bars.
The house Batlló in the Eixample district on the lively shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43 was built by the rebuilding of a house dating back to 1877, which architect Emilio Sala Cortese performed.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally existed on the demolition of the old and the construction of a completely new building, but ultimately he agreed to Gaudí's idea of an unusual and also cheaper conversion.
However, Antoni Gaudí did not design the house Casa Batlló alone.
He worked with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
The decorations for the representative apartment of the real estate owner and the use of mosaics on the facade were his idea.
However, numerous other artists and sculptors also cooperated in the design of the facade.
The joint work on the designs for Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful cooperation between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí's house Casa Milá in the Park Güell, where there are also other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after his completion, the house was given the nickname "Knochenhaus" by the local inhabitants of its organic forms.
Others, in turn, called it the special window opening mechanism because of the "walking house".
It is also said that at the top of the building is the sword of St. George, the Patron of Catalonia.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motifs.
Gaudí designed a unique central heating system for the time being with ventilation channels and typical fireplaces.
Something bizarre is already motivating her 45-degree slope.
In his work, Gaudí consistently ignored all the building regulations of the time and was by no means deceived by them.
Before the start of construction, he obtained from the city the corresponding building permit, but the information he provided on the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later the city fathers were so horrified at the completion that they demanded remedy.
The Councillors also supported, among other things, the fact that construction with its pillars even intervened in the public sidewalk.
However, changes were no longer made, quite the contrary - only fifteen days after the call for the district to do so, Josep Batlló filed an application for permission to rent the two highest floors of the house - and it was given to him promptly.
The owner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a social shop, on the third floor there were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey building runs through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
All right angles and straight lines were removed and replaced by curved and curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept for the interconnection of rooms.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon doors and thus a larger society could easily chat without having to refrain from some intimacy in more confidential conversations.
The house received a rather unusual roof and two more floors, thanks to Gaudí's conversion, apart from a new facade.
Gaudí's play with the light as well as the blue and white glazed tiles with which the courtyard is dressed and the light courts is impressive.
The play of these two colors gives all floors of the house a maximum of light.
He simply made use of the principle that white reflects the light better than dark colors that absorb the sunlight on the contrary.
The Casa Batlló house, which was included in the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005, can be visited by anyone today.
On the first floor the most spacious and magnificent apartment is made available to the public.
The owners of the house only decided in the year on this step and this on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous Creator.
When it was found that this was a fairly profitable business, the visits were maintained, and they were extended to other common and attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
However, the price for visiting the building monument is not a paparazzi, it is 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and owners of tourist visas receive a 20% discount.
This amount exceeds the admission prices to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
Anyone who wants to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers should try to make friends with one of the home dwellers and visit him at home.
