More and more parents want human monitoring devices to control the kids
The fear of their own children grows and so more and more parents are considering monitoring them via GPS.
The system that was originally invented for the detection of cars can be found just as well in people, which would also be helpful in such cases, as recently as the nine-year-old Anička Janatková disappeared.
The device is currently about the size of a cigarette box but soon it may not be bigger than a wristwatch.
Many people have put the case of the disappeared Anička in fear and terror, so they look for ways and means to better protect their children.
Also for the price of harming their privacy.
"We try to tell everyone that this is not about spying, but about an effective means of reducing the likelihood of tragedy," says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of GPS tracking devices on the Czech market.
"I admit that in individual cases there may be abuse of such devices, for example if you put someone in your pocket without him knowing about it, but we have not yet had such a case."
"Most customers really buy it for security reasons," Pilin adds.
In his opinion, however, the child should always know what purpose the "box" serves and how to use it in an emergency.
However, children's psychologist Dana Bočková points out that if a child doesn't like to wear such a thing, it just gets rid of him.
"Very small children also show great creativity when it comes to deliberately losing certain things if they don't want to be controlled."
"Even the cell phones awakened great expectations at first among the parents, but they can be turned off just as easily as these new monitoring devices," says Ms. Bočková.
In their opinion, it is also disputed whether such an institution actually helps in the event of an attack.
