A longer index finger than a ring finger means a lower risk of cancer
Men whose index finger is longer than the ring finger are obviously at lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the surprising result of a study published on Wednesday by the British Journal of Cancer.
This should be related to the mirror of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results show that the relative length of the fingers can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer, and in particular in men up to sixty," said the co-author of the study, Ros Eeles, professor at the Cancer Research Institute at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help to determine which men should necessarily undergo a prostate cancer test, especially if genetic risks or other risk factors are present, such as family health stress, added Mrs Eeles.
During the period 1994-2009, she and her colleagues in Britain persecuted more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer, but also 3,000 healthy men.
With more than half of the participants in the study, the index finger of the right hand was shorter than the ring finger.
For these men, the probability of prostate cancer was the same as for 19 percent of the men whose ring and index fingers were the same.
However, in men whose index finger was longer than the ring finger, this risk decreased by 33 percent, in men up to sixty even by 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers mentioned, which already form at prenatal age, clearly reflects the different levels of sex hormones that the child was exposed to in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index finger.
Previous research has shown that testosterone is accelerating the growth of prostate cancer.
Václav Pačes, a leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, said ČTK that this study was readily known to him, yet he did not consider the relationship between the finger length and the cancer risk to be "exposed".
