The democracy movement in Latin America is becoming stronger, as is the support of private companies.
Crime is a bigger problem than unemployment.
In many parts of the region, the influence of Brazil is greater than that of the United States.
The Latinobarómetro survey, conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist, came to this conclusion.
This survey has been conducted regularly since 1995 and shows the change of opinion in this region.
Two facts are particularly evident in this year's September and October survey.
First, the good mood in Latin America
and, secondly, the growing interest in democracy and its most important institutions.
In many countries on the South American Pacific coast, the democratic movement has increased strongly (see Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy has grown by about 6% annually since 2002, the number of democracy supporters rose from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
This trend can also be seen in Mexico, where the economy has recovered since the sharp collapse last year.
But only half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the most populous countries in the region, are convinced democrats, which reduces the regional average (see Chart 2).
About 44% of respondents said that they are satisfied with the democratic practice of their country. These are as many as last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (Graph 3).
About 34% trust the Congress of their country and 45% trust their government. Both values correspond to those of last year, but show a marked increase compared to 2003 (17% and 24%).
A decade ago, Latin America's economic crises undermined its efforts to increase democracy.
This continued during the global economic crisis, possibly because the countries of Latin America experienced only a short recession and recovered quickly.
In addition, the poor were caught up in a stronger social network.
(According to reports from the UN Economic Commission for Latin America this week, the poverty rate in Latin America rose only slightly in 2009 and fell again by 32% this year.)
However, there are strong mood differences from country to country (see Diagram 4).
Brazil's strong economy and the popularity of outgoing President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva are reflected in a widespread sense of progress.
In Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more noticeable and violent crimes have increased, this is less the case.
Only for the second time since the start of the survey do many respondents in Latin America see a greater problem in crime in their country than in unemployment (see Chart 5).
About 31% say that either they themselves or a family member were victims of a crime last year. However, compared to 38% last year, the values have fallen and thus reach the lowest level since 1995.
The increase in economic performance is reflected in the increased support for the private and market economy: around 71% of respondents across the region indicated that the private economy is indispensable for development, in 2007 it was 56% (see Chart 6).
