Coccel was not part of the research team.
"This work is a novel because it shows that in basic biochemical processes and structures one element can be replaced by another," Cockell added.
This discovery was not accidental.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon from NASA's Astrobiological Institute, which led the study, chose the Mono Lake because of its high arsenic content.
Since arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, they assumed that microbes, which are both exposed, may be able to replace one element by the other.
"The toxicity of the arsenic is mainly based on the fact that it behaves chemically similar to phosphorus."
"This makes it difficult for organisms to distinguish one element from another."
"But the difference is so great that arsenic works differently than phosphorus. It gets into our biochemical system, where it almost all lubricates," explains Anbar.
The researchers exposed the bacterium GFAJ-1 to an increasing arsenic concentration. It adapted and grew.
Although the microbe grows better in phosphorus, but that it can also survive in arsenic shows that an arsenic-based form of life can occur naturally, either on earth or on another planet or moon, on which arsenic occurs more frequently.
