Zapatero and the red line of Germany
Berlin has opted for the maintenance of the euro, but at the same time has set conditions for the whole of the European Union.
The tensions in the markets have triggered a double response from the government.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has presented new adaptation measures, starting with tax reductions for small and medium-sized enterprises, the regulation of temporary work companies or the abolition of the EUR 426 support for unemployed people who do not receive unemployment benefit, until the privatisation of 49 per cent of AENA, the management of Barajas and El Prat airports and 30 per cent of the state lottery.
On the other hand, the Deputy Head of Government, Elena Salgado, with the help of former President Felipe González, supports the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel as responsible for the current crisis.
How are these processes to be understood?
It should be anticipated that Merkel's position is not an error in her public relations work.
On the contrary, it is a new round in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
Germany takes on a fundamentally new perspective on the design of our future, which conflicts with the maintenance of the traditions of a large part of its partners.
In view of the resistance in Europe, three possible ways out of the crisis are beginning to speculate in Germany.
The first: a strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the south would have to leave the euro area.
The second: The reintroduction of the German Mark - although it currently sounds more like Science Fiction - is supported by a majority of the public opinion, about 50 percent of the population.
The third: a redesign of the euro according to German proposals. This means: more macro-economic control; strict budgetary management; punishment of countries that violate the rules; possibly the suspension of payments by some countries and the extension of the costs of potential adjustment measures to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has stood out for some time. Therefore, there are no excuses now.
First in 2009, both the IMF and the European Commission created incentives for deficits and the German government withdrew from the constitutional reform to prevent this from 2016.
This was the first sign of dissociation between what Germany considered necessary (strict tax plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second sign was the Central European country, when Merkel painfully postponed the decision to rescue Greece.
But the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, both public and public, was absolutely against a rescue from Greece.
Finally, in the last few days of October, Merkel has come out again with a clear position, calling for a reform of the European Union's agreements to enable a country to be rescued while at the same time obliging private lenders to bear some of the costs.
This position was interpreted as anti-European, as it pushed forward the Irish crisis and all the following.
But her proposal, albeit slightly sweetened, has been accepted, and in the coming months we will be participating in the reform of the European Union, which will allow for these measures from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that does not intend to exceed it.
It says to everyone that, even though unpopular measures must be taken now, the old functioning of the euro will no longer exist from this date.
2013 will be the year of birth of a new currency area in which the countries which are opposed will be severely punished, forced to declare themselves insolvent and, in this case, the private sector will have to bear some of the costs.
Germany shows us that we need to take a tough growth rate, with high savings and investment rates, moderation of consumption, improvement of productivity and competitiveness, and positive external balances.
The other alternative, which is based on debt and construction with huge holes in the balance of payments, as suggested by Spain in boom times, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we would do badly not to understand it.
It is not just a matter of reducing the government deficit to three percent by 2013.
The demands are much harder.
And the worst thing we could do under these conditions is cheat on ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will pass into more tranquility.
And that we will take advantage of the opportunities offered to us by spring 2013.
It seems that Zapatero understood this as well, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after the meeting with the big companies last Saturday and the announcement of new measures from yesterday) indicates that despite the criticism of Merkel the hypothesis of creating order in their own house has prepared their way.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it doesn't look like something would change.
Among the possibilities considered is that we should not exclude the euro area packed with few serious countries.
In this case, Germany could still tell us that it warned us.
Sports and regulatory environment
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against the Ajax show ingenuity, but not the will to avoid a penalty.
The exclusion allegedly raised by two players of the Real Madrid (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the game of 23 November against the Ajax in the Champions League resulted in a lot of ink being poured on whether or not it was an unportable act and whether or not both players should be punished by the UEFA.
As is generally known, the two players lost time a few minutes before playing (their team had already clearly won) and played several fouls so that the referee showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid would lead its group, the two players will comply with the required penalty at the next match against the Auxerre and thus enter the next game stage without cards.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee punished the club's coach, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is more often found in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten but in this sport - rules.
Part of the debate on the case presented is that a team of the Real Madrid Football Club (who in his anthems pretended to be noble and honoured, and on other occasions punished his players for similar incidents) played the leading role in this, and on the dramatization by Mourinho, who added an episode more to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate is about whether or not it does not explicitly prohibit the conduct of the statutes from contradicting the principles of sport, that is, whether these actions constitute a circumvention of the rules. In fact, this approach adheres to the statutes of sport, but seems to be circumventing its sense.
On this matter, the damage caused to the sports spirit should be investigated.
The sports spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not compromised by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to avoid the opposing players from taking unfair advantage of the opposing team. Nor did that happen.
The paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not correspond to what we usually understand by misappropriation or circumvention of rules, because the circumvention of the rule was not done secretly to avoid a penalty, but it should be as conspicuous as possible so that it is punished by the referee.
The players waited and gladly assumed the penalty.
Another question is what kind of advantage did the offenders draw from the intentional fouls.
Here it should be stressed that the rival was not brought into a more unfavourable position or gained benefits for the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that the own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club then does not have these players.
The advantage obviously is that players will start the next game phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it’s a long-term, up to a certain degree, unknown advantage, since the team could eventually also leave. In addition, the players get a penalty with this procedure and move into the second card cycle, in which they leave with a card less than in the first cycle due to card accumulation.
It is therefore not so clear whether this is really an advantage.
Finally, such practices are not directed against the spirit of sport, which also includes strategic decisions in order to derive the greatest benefit from the rules.
In this case, the players did not want to circumvent sanctions (that would actually be a clear case of circumvention of rules), they preferred to choose when to submit to them.
They made a strategic decision without evading a punishment or fleeing it.
Although the border between the inventive step and the regulatory environment is blurred, I believe that this is a clear case of inventive step.
I have the impression that the polemics came about as a result of two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the type of provoked rule transmission.
The damage caused by these actions to the principles of sport is less ethical than rather aesthetic.
